Across the landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the coastline Chile conquered after a bloody conflict over the exploitation of natural resources in the 19th century is still alive, as is the longing of its people to travel to the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes have risen today more than ever, in decades, as Bolivia awaits the International Court of Justice's ruling on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the dynamics, a spirit of unity and calm, and naturally awaits the result with a positive look," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
