John Edward: Language skills are essential for the world's citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a background in academic excellence, which continued into 2018, with yet another series of outstanding exam results, which were simply further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sports, the arts, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible level of service to students and their parents.
The goal of independent schools is to prepare their students for the next and highest educational grades, the professional career they will choose and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational field that can design and implement a school curriculum on-demand, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desirable elective course in schools.
Nelson Mandela had said: "If you talk to someone in a language they understand, then what you say goes into their head.
If you speak to him in his own language, what you say goes into his heart."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot simply rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year's exams, we find that languages are at the top of the performance tables, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a baccalaureate A degree.
Data gathered from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved an A baccalaureate degree in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also had an A grade.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
Languages today, as a elective course, are considered as important as courses involving science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Employment and Skills Committee in 2014 revealed that, with regard to the reasons why employers found it difficult to fill vacancies, a 17-percent figure involved a lack of language skills.
Therefore, the need to acquire language skills is becoming increasingly imperative so that young people are prepared for their future professional careers.
Since more future employment opportunities require language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career one will choose, if one has learned a second language, one will have a real advantage in the future, because of this skill one will be able to utilize throughout one's life.
If one is able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, then automatically this multilingual person will have an advantage over competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents were unable to speak any foreign language well enough to have a conversation, while French was the only language to speak a double-digit percentage of respondents (15 percent).
For this reason, investing in language teaching today is important for today's children.
Knowledge of many languages, especially the languages of developing economies, will give children better opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered most important to the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
For whatever your child is interested in, there will always be some languages to choose from in independent schools, which have qualified teaching staff in this area.
Scotland's independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds for them.
One cannot deny today that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be extremely important for the future of the country, so this reality should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered truly "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, multiculturalism and excellence for Scottish youth.
They have to.
John Edward is director of the Councils of Independent Schools of Scotland.
