Harvard students attend classes on how to get enough rest
This year, a new course at Harvard University seeks all undergraduate students to sleep more in an effort to combat the growing culture of all-night study by consuming a lot of caffeine.
One academic discovered that students at the world's number 1 university often do not know basic things, e.g. how to take care of themselves.
Charles Chaser, a Harvard Medical School professor of Sleep Medicine and a qualified doctor at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, 'Why am I learning about this just now, in my senior year?'
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, first started this year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and athletic performance, as well as improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to include the course when it was found that students were deprived of sleep within the week to a significant degree.
The hourly course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is the image of a student dormitory, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes and books, to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is affected by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not directly change the behavior of students.
We believe, however, that they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know the health effects when you choose to smoke," added Professor Chaser.
The culture of being proud because you studied all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students means that sleep deprivation is a problem that is growing.
Sufficient sleep, good quality, should be the students' "secret weapon" to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, even to avoid weight gain, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into a state of starvation, resulting in a lasting feeling of hunger.
Raymond Shaw, a 19-year-old Californian who studies Chemistry and Natural Biology, helped Professor Chaser plan the course, having attended one of his classes last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said his class opened his eyes and inspired him to push for a course across the campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to attend a similar program before starting their studies at this highly competitive educational institution.
Professor Chaser recommended that students set up a notice of the time they should go to bed, as well as an alarm clock for waking time, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic displays and LED lighting, which can defuse the circadian rhythm, leading to sleep problems.
