The National Trust eavesdrops on the secret life of bats
New research conducted on an estate in the Highlands of Scotland seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape when hunting their food.
The findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help plan future actions to protect the environment.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will explore the habits of the common nanobat and microbat, as well as the brown toad and the mytilla of Dobpenton at Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the estate to monitor bat activities throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile searches using hand detectors.
Analysis of the sound of all recordings by experts will ascertain the frequency of bat calls, as well as what species have this behavior.
A habitat map and an exhibition will then be created to form a detailed picture of their behaviour on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, a natural environment protection consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to identify the benefits of habitat management, such as grassland creation and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined significantly since the last century.
They are threatened by the building and development projects that affect the places where they roost and destroy their habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting are also a danger, as are fly duct tapes and some chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes to catch their prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to identify insects and obstacles in the course of their flight.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, considers bats very important.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct investigations, inspect the places where bats roost and sometimes rescue them.
The organization has also set up Scotland's first and only bat shelter exclusively on the Threeve estate, in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland's ten bat species live.
The estate manager, David Thompson, states that the estate is the ideal ground for bats.
"Here at Threeve we have an excellent area for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of big trees and an ideal habitat.
There's still a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we're doing here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to increase their populations."
He stresses that it is important to first check for the existence of bats before any house maintenance work, as the destruction of a single nest with young could kill up to 400 females and young, possibly eliminating the entire local population.
Bats are protected species and are prohibited from killing, harassing or disturbing their privacy, or destroying their nests.
Elizabeth Ferrell, an executive of the Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland encouraged the public to offer his assistance.
He said: "There's a lot to learn about our bats and a lot of our species we just don't know the evolution of their population."
