All conditions are now met for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they were forced to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war broke out in 2011.
Another six million people still living in the country are in need of humanitarian aid.
Al Mualem said that aid to rebuild the destroyed country is welcomed by the Syrian government.
However, he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid nor assistance from countries that supported the uprising.
Europe locks victory at the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup, defeating the U.S. team with a final score of 16.5 versus 10.5 at the Le Golf National golf course, outside Paris in France.
The American team has now been defeated 6 times in a row on European soil and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe again took first place, as Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team reached the 14.5 points needed to defeat the United States.
U.S. team star Phil Mikkelston, who fought hard during the longest duration of the tournament, threw his shot into the water in the par-3 16th hole, ceding the victory to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shone throughout his rounds and thus became 1 out of 4 players who scored 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament began in 1979.
American Jordan Spith was defeated at 5&4 by the European team's lowest ranked player, Danish Thorbjorn Olsen.
The world's best-ranked player, Dustin Johnson, scored 2 and 1 against Ian Puller from England, who may have played his last game in a Ryder Cup.
Spanish veteran eight Ridder Cups, Sergio Garcia was crowned the most winning European of all time in the tournament with a total of 25.5 points.
"I usually don't cry, but today I can't help myself.
It's been a difficult year.
I'm grateful to Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm very happy we got the cup back.
It's all for the team and I'm glad I was able to help," Garcia said excitedly after the European victory.
He gives the baton to his compatriot John Ram, who defeated American golf legend Tiger Woods 2&1 in an individual game on Sunday.
"I feel incredible pride in beating Tiger Woods, I grew up admiring this guy," said 23-year-old Ram.
Woods lost in all four of his games in France and now has a career record in the Rider Cup 13-21-3.
Unusual stats for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 major titles and has been surpassed only by Jack Niklaus.
The U.S. team had a difficult weekend to find a target, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas, and Tony Fino, who played high-level golf throughout the tournament.
American leader Jim Farrick spoke after his team's disappointing performance, "I'm proud of these kids, they fought it.
At times this morning we put a lot of pressure on Europe.
We fought hard.
Congratulations to Thomas.
He's a great leader.
All 12 of his players played very well.
We will regroup, work with the U.S. PGA and the Ryder Cup Committee and move forward.
I love these 12 kids and I'm proud to be their leader.
We have to admit it.
They were better than us."
Red tide update: Concentrations decreasing in Pinellas, Manati and Sarasota provinces
The latest announcement from the Florida Pisces and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in Red Tide concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, conditions of uneven spots are seen in areas of the Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier provinces, which suggests a decrease in concentrations.
A stain of the Red Tide extends over about 130 miles of coastline from the northern Pinella province to the southern Lee province.
Spots are located about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough province, but in less places than last week.
Red Tide has also been observed in the province of Pasco.
Moderate concentrations were recorded on the coast and off the coast of Pinellas Province last week, low to high concentrations were recorded off the coast in Hillsborough Province, background concentrations to high concentrations in Manati Province, background concentrations to high concentrations on the coast or off the coast in Sarasota Province, background concentrations to moderate concentrations in Charlotte Province, background concentrations to high concentrations in the coast or off the coast.
Disturbances in the respiratory system continue to be recorded in the provinces of Pinellas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory tract disturbances were reported in northwest Florida in the past week.
